components.text: [center][size=27][b]The Celonis Delivery Delay Prediction algorithm uses your historical process data to train a model that is able to predict possible delays for currently open items. The algorithm classifies the already closed cases as 'delayed' or 'not delayed' (i.e. 1 or 0) and then predicts for the open cases due in a specified amount of days. In order to adapt the model to your individual demands, please follow the instructions in the Model Setup sheets 1 - 5.[/b][/size][/center]
[left][size=14]Select the activity which corresponds to 'an item leaving your warehouse', i.e., the issuing of the goods. For example, 'Record Goods Issue'.[/size][/left]

components.message: Make sure to rerun the script after changing the parameters here, otherwise they will not update in Python

components.text: [left][size=14]Define here what your due date is, i.e.,which date field is the target date that you want to reach. In O2C this usually means the date you want a delivery to leave your warehouse so that it has enough time to reach the customer by the confirmed delivery date. In SAP the standard field for this is VBEP.WADAT In the standard case you would put (PU_LAST(VBAP,VBEP.WADAT)):[/size][/left]

[left][size=14]Specify here the buffer amount of days you allow an item to leave your ware house 
after the due date and still be considered on time: [/size][/left]

[b][size=25] Are you running a tryout or are you already live?
[/size][/b]

[left][size=14]If you try to run this on a non-live Data Model please select 'demo' in order to set the reference date to the date of the last data extraction, if you are live select 'live': [/size][/left]

variables.value:

     WHEN "EKPO"."LOEKZ" = 'S' THEN 'locked'
     WHEN "EKPO"."LOEKZ" = 'L' THEN 'deleted'
     ELSE "EKPO"."LOEKZ"
END
